# Deployment and observability

These rules apply once a project deploys somewhere beyond a local machine. They are
deliberately platform-agnostic (a container host, a serverless platform, a PaaS all
qualify) — record the actual target in `90-project-context.mdc`.

## Environments

- Maintain at least two separate environments — staging/preview and production — with
  separate databases and separate secrets. Never point a staging environment at the
  production database "just to test something."
- Configuration that differs by environment (URLs, feature flags, log level) comes from
  environment variables or a config service, never from a hardcoded branch in code
  (`if (env === 'production')` scattered through business logic is a smell — isolate it
  to a config module).
- Secrets are injected at deploy time by the platform's secret store or CI secrets, never
  committed, never baked into a container image layer (see `10-security-popia.mdc`).

## Containerization (where applicable)

- Use a multi-stage Dockerfile: build dependencies and compile in one stage, copy only
  the production artifact and runtime dependencies into a slim final image.
- Run the container process as a non-root user.
- Pin the base image to a specific digest or minor version, not `latest`.

## Health checks and readiness

- Expose a lightweight liveness endpoint (process is up) separate from a readiness
  endpoint (dependencies — database, cache — are reachable) if the platform supports
  the distinction. A liveness check must not depend on the database; a crashed database
  should not cause the orchestrator to kill and restart a healthy process in a loop.
- A deploy is not "done" until the new version passes its readiness check — do not
  route traffic to a version that hasn't confirmed it can serve requests.

## Structured logging

- Log in structured JSON (not freeform strings) in any environment beyond local dev, so
  logs are queryable: `{ timestamp, level, message, requestId, ...context }`.
- Never log personal information, secrets, full request/response bodies, or auth
  tokens — this is a hard stop carried over from `10-security-popia.mdc`, restated here
  because logging is exactly where it most often leaks by accident (e.g. logging an
  entire request object for "debugging").
- Include a correlation/request ID generated at the edge and threaded through every log
  line for that request, so a single failure can be traced end-to-end.

## Error tracking and alerting

- Wire unhandled exceptions and unhandled promise rejections to an error-tracking
  service (e.g. Sentry-class tooling) rather than relying on log-scraping to notice
  production errors.
- Alert on symptoms a user would notice (error rate, latency, availability), not only on
  infrastructure metrics (CPU, memory) that may be fine while the application is broken.
- Every alert must have a documented first response step — an alert with no runbook is
  noise.

## Rollback

- Every deploy mechanism must support rolling back to the previous version without a
  fresh build (redeploy the prior image/artifact). Know how to do this before you need
  it, not while an incident is in progress.
- Database migrations that ship alongside a deploy should be backward-compatible with
  the previous application version for at least one deploy cycle, so a rollback doesn't
  require a matching schema rollback.

## Hard stops

- Do not point any non-production environment at the production database.
- Do not log personal information, secrets, or full request bodies under any
  circumstance.
- Do not ship a deploy pipeline with no rollback path.
- Do not treat "the container is running" as equivalent to "the service is healthy" —
  readiness must check real dependencies.
